title: Switching Up Education

###Pandemic Party Games

Three years ago, my friends and I holed up together in a dorm lounge while a Nor'easter that grounded every single one of our flights home for spring break ravaged the world outside our little den. Fully grown trees were being ripped up out of the ground, but we hardly noticed, as we were at each other's throats. One girl in the group had brought a game for us to play: Pandemic, and needless to say, we made it not very far at all. It turns out that we were completely incapable of collaborating, but the game completely lacked a sense of urgency for us. Believe me, the irony of not being able to collaborate to stop a pandemic after the rollercoaster 2020 has been is not lost on me. Looking back, though, Pandemic was a huge lesson both in teamwork and in taking things seriously.

Today, my parents and I made a multi-stop journey across the state of Massachusetts to procure the Nintendo Switch. After store after store sold out right as we pulled into the parking lot, we finally arrived at the Target in Fenway. We bolted up several escalators, and we ultimately made it just in time to snatch up the last Nintendo Switch available in the entire state of Massachusetts (no exaggeration, we checked online availability). When I picked games, I stuck to Nintendo classics, like *Mario Kart*, but two other games caught my eye: *Civilization III* and *Pandemic*. I guess coming across *Pandemic* in the middle of a pandemic several years after my failed first attempt is what some would call full circle.

*Civilization III* is a game in which the player builds an empire from the ground up, loosely based on history, economics, diplomacy, and strategy. The player can start wars or pursue peace, and they can rule as a dictator or as a leader beloved by the empire. The game is loosely based on history, although it can also take the player into the future. Despite all the paths you can take, the end result is the same: you learn about history (loosely speaking). You learn how the world we inhabit came to be. 

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Pandemic* relies on a similar premise of a map-oriented game, but a different skillset entirely. Whereas Civilization III encourages individual leadership, *Pandemic* relies upon a team of players to coordinate their individual skills to stop four deadly viruses from wiping out mankind. Each player is assigned one of several roles, but they are absolutely powerless without the help of their teammates. Without a global and interdisciplinary effort at cooperation, the world is doomed.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

While video games serve as a nice distraction from the COVID-19 pandemic, they also serve as an educational tool. Some older generations are still rather leery around video games, looking at them as a form of mindless entertainment designed to "rot" kids' brains. Educational experts, however, have published a plethora of articles about how vital video games are for learning. In a news article published by Stanford called [Playing to learn: Panelists at Stanford discussion say using games as an educational tool provides opportunities for deeper learning](https://news.stanford.edu/2013/03/01/games-education-tool-030113/#:~:text=Interaction%20and%20opportunities%20to%20make,of%20educational%20games%2C%20experts%20say.&text=Games%20help%20us%20develop%20non,succeed%2C%20according%20to%20the%20panelists.), R. F. MacKay says that learning often is a product of freedom and choice (MacKay). When given choices, children challenging themselves more, making video games an ideal educational tool.

Previous generations have had the tendency to scoff at and rebuke video games, and yet they demand that students rely upon those skills later in life. For example, when I took the LSAT as a junior in college, there was an entire section dubbed "Logic Games." While I find myself to be a fairly logical person and rather good at mathematics, I don't know how to play games. In school, I learned how to integrate a curve and how to memorize nearly useless facts (in a real world context where those facts are readily available), but I never learned how to think. There were no choices. Our daily schedule was comprised of "sit here, don't talk, do this worksheet, eat your lunch quickly, do that worksheet." Learning was a dictatorship. It's as simple as that. The Logic Games were the weakest part of my test because the current education system deprived me of the opportunity to learn the way children are supposed to learn: by playing. 

###A New Approach to Education

Aside from teaching students basic skills and hinting at history, games could do more. At Boston College, a former professor of mine, [Joesph Nugent](https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas/departments/english/people/faculty-directory/joseph--nugent.html), is experimenting with classic Irish literature and virtual reality. A new generation of educators is emerging, emphasizing interaction as essential to education. Of course, this will present its own challenges. Education will no longer simply require teachers, but coders. Academia will have to resign itself to adaptation, despite its previous rigidity and insistence on tradition. 

It will likely take a long time before education reaches its potential as a fun, interactive process. We have tied ourselves down to mediums that no longer serve as a complete representation of the human learning experience. James Coltrain and Stephen Ramsay touch on this in [Can Video Games Be Humanities Scholarship?](https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/read/untitled-f2acf72c-a469-49d8-be35-67f9ac1e3a60/section/10c2899a-d78c-40d2-b293-f828d3a1b3e9) from *Debates in the Digital Humanities 2019.* They say, 
> "Matters such as 'citation,' 'thesis,' 'abstract,' and the generic traditions of scholarly rhetoric need to be viewed not as necessary components to enabling something to be deemed scholarly, but rather as the apparatus of a specific genre and its medium. To talk about video games is to talk about both a new genre and a new medium: one that will require its own, perhaps quite different, scholarly apparatus."

While it is too late to give my generation the educational necessity of choice, games can be brought into the academic fold before it is too late for other children to reach their potential.
